":{"1332–before 5 July 1365":"1332–before 5 July 1365","1332–1365":"1332–1365","1320–1365":"1320–1365","1364–1427":"1364–1427","1346–1427":"1346–1427","1337–Male":"1337–Deceased","1300–Female":"1300–Deceased","after 1346":"after 1346","1337":"1337","1346":"1346","1300":"1300","1332":"1332","1365":"1365","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","before 5 July 1365":"before 5 July 1365","1427":"1427","Raith, Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ayr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Scottish: locative name from the royal burgh of Ayr in SW Scotland.","2  Scottish: it could also be a variant of   Ayer   or   Ayre  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ayre","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Ayer  ."]},{"name":"Ayer","meanings":["English and Scottish: from Middle English <i>eir</i>, <i>eyr</i> ‘heir’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>heyr</i>, Old French <i>(h)eir</i>, Latin <i>heres</i>). Forms such as <i>Richard le Heyer</i> were frequent in Middle English, denoting a man who was well known to be the heir to the main property in a particular locality, either one who had already inherited or one with great expectations.","English: from the Anglo-Norman French and Middle English personal name <i>Aier</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Agihari</i>).","English: variant of   Hair  ."]},{"name":"Air","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Ayr  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Ayr was born in 1332, in Ayrs